Report_Text_ENGLISH <-
"The purpose of the annual WIDA ACCESS for ELLs assessment is to measure an English learner (EL) student's level of academic English language proficiency
(ELP) as required Federal statute and in the State ESSA Plan. Educators and parents can monitor students' growth in ELP by comparing current ACCESS for
ELLs score results with previous scores. When a student's level of ELP reaches the level the state and/or the local school system have established as full English
proficiency, parents and educators are confident the student can participate in school instruction and assessment in English without language support. This report
addresses your student's English language proficiency (ELP) growth relative to similar students. This report can also identify if your student is on track to full
proficiency in English.

Proficiency: The WIDA ACCESS for ELLs Individual Student Report provides students and parents with the student's Overall Composite Scale Score and
Proficiency Level. The overall composite scale score results from a combination of listening, speaking, reading, and writing domain scale scores. An interpretation
of the scale scores results in six proficiency levels. From lowest to highest, the proficiency levels are: 1-Entering, 2-Emerging, 3-Developing, 4-Expanding,
5-Bridging, and 6-Reaching. This report presents two consecutive years of your student's overall composite scale scores and proficiency levels. Please see
your student's ACCESS for ELLs Individual Student Report for more information on your child's scale scores and proficiency levels for the individual language
domains and the oral, literacy, and comprehension composites.

Growth: The Georgia Student Growth Model for English Language Proficiency (GSGM for ELP) compares the ELP growth each English learner makes in one
year relative to EL students across the state with similar prior year ELP and in the same grade. The model tells us how an EL student's growth in English proficiency
compares to other same-grade students with similar proficiency in the prior year. The term student growth percentile (SGP) describes this growth. Student growth
percentiles range from 1 (lowest growth) to 99 (highest growth). Percentiles are not percent correct scores, and do not reflect students' levels of ELP. Students
with low ELP levels can achieve high student growth percentiles if their English proficiency has increased from the previous year's assessment as compared to their
like peers.

We hope that this report will help you understand your child's English language development. This English language proficiency (ELP) growth report can form
the basis for conversations with your student's teachers to discuss questions such as the following:
      *  How can I help my child reach full English language proficiency in an average period (3-5 years)?
      *  Is my child's academic English language proficiency growth on track to reach the Expanding Level 4.3 next year?
      *  What could be keeping my children from typical growth in English language proficiency like their friends?

For more Information about student ELP growth in Georgia, please visit GSGM for ELP:
https://www.gadoe.org/School-Improvement/Federal-Programs/Pages/Georgia-Student-Growth-Model-for-English-Language-Proficiency.aspx"

